specJson.label: AdaBoost Regression Train
specJson.description:
Adaboost, introduced in 1995 by Freund and Schapire, is a machine learning meta-algorithm which can be used in conjunction with many other types of learning algorithms to improve performance.

The core principle of AdaBoost is to fit a sequence of weak learners (i.e., models that are only slightly better than random guessing, such as small decision trees) on repeatedly modified versions of the data. The predictions from all of them are then combined through a weighted majority vote (or sum) to produce the final prediction. The data modifications at each so-called boosting iteration consist of applying weights to each of the training samples. For each successive iteration, the sample weights are individually modified and the learning algorithm is reapplied to the reweighted data. At a given step, those training examples that were incorrectly predicted by the boosted model induced at the previous step have their weights increased, whereas the weights are decreased for those that were predicted correctly. As iterations proceed, examples that are difficult to predict receive ever-increasing influence. Each subsequent weak learner is thereby forced to concentrate on the examples that are missed by the previous ones in the sequence.

Reference:
+ <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AdaBoost>
+ <https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/ensemble.html#adaboost>

params.description: Feature column names. Only values in numeric type are possible.

params.label: Label Column
params.description: The column designated for the labels of data. It should be numeric type as it is for regression.

params.label: Maximum Depth
params.description: The maximum depth of the base estimator. In this Brightics Studio, the base estimator for Adaboost Regression model is Decision Tree Regression model. Note that it is one of the main parameters to tune to obtain good results by controlling the complexity of the base estimmators.

params.label: Number of Estimators
params.description: The maximum number of estimators at which boosting is terminated. In case of perfect fit, the learning procedure is stopped early. Increasing `Number of Estimators` increases the number of iterations, and allows the sample weights to gain greater amplitude. This translates into 1) more weak classifiers to combine at the end, and 2) more variations in the decision boundaries of these classifiers. Put together these effects lead to more complex decision boundaries. Note that it is one of the main parameters to tune to obtain good results.

params.label: Learning Rate
params.description: Learning rate shrinks the contribution of each classifier by `Learning Rate`. Decreasing the `Learning Rate` reduces the amplitude of the sample weights at each step. This translates into smaller variations of the weighted data points and therefore fewer differences between the weak classifier decision boundaries. There is a trade-off between `Learning Rate` and `Number of Estimators`.

params.label: Loss
params.description:
The loss function to use when updating the weights after each boosting iteration.
   - Available Options : `LINEAR`, `SQUARE`, `EXPONENTIAL`

params.label: Seed
params.description: Random seed. Use the same seed in order to reproduce the same results.

md:
# AdaBoost Regression Train This function trains an adaboost regression model. ## Description Adaboost, introduced in 1995 by Freund and Schapire, is a machine learning meta-algorithm which can be used in conjunction with many other types of learning algorithms to improve performance. The core principle of AdaBoost is to fit a sequence of weak learners (i.e., models that are only slightly better than random guessing, such as small decision trees) on repeatedly modified versions of the data. The predictions from all of them are then combined through a weighted majority vote (or sum) to produce the final prediction. The data modifications at each so-called boosting iteration consist of applying weights to each of the training samples. For each successive iteration, the sample weights are individually modified and the learning algorithm is reapplied to the reweighted data. At a given step, those training examples that were incorrectly predicted by the boosted model induced at the previous step have their weights increased, whereas the weights are decreased for those that were predicted correctly. As iterations proceed, examples that are difficult to predict receive ever-increasing influence. Each subsequent weak learner is thereby forced to concentrate on the examples that are missed by the previous ones in the sequence. Reference: + + ## Properties ### VA #### INPUT 1. **table***: (Table) Training data in a Table. It must contain at least one column for labels. #### OUTPUT 1. **model**: (Model) Trained Adaboost Regression model. #### PARAMETER 1. **Feature Columns***: Feature column names. Only values in numeric type are possible. 2. **Label Column***: The column designated for the labels of data. It should be numeric type as it is for regression. 3. **Maximum Depth**: The maximum depth of the base estimator. In this Brightics Studio, the base estimator for Adaboost Regression model is Decision Tree Regression model. Note that it is one of the main parameters to tune to obtain good results by controlling the complexity of the base estimmators. 4. **Number of Estimators**: The maximum number of estimators at which boosting is terminated. In case of perfect fit, the learning procedure is stopped early. Increasing `Number of Estimators` increases the number of iterations, and allows the sample weights to gain greater amplitude. This translates into 1) more weak classifiers to combine at the end, and 2) more variations in the decision boundaries of these classifiers. Put together these effects lead to more complex decision boundaries. Note that it is one of the main parameters to tune to obtain good results. 5. **Learning Rate**: Learning rate shrinks the contribution of each classifier by `Learning Rate`. Decreasing the `Learning Rate` reduces the amplitude of the sample weights at each step. This translates into smaller variations of the weighted data points and therefore fewer differences between the weak classifier decision boundaries. There is a trade-off between `Learning Rate` and `Number of Estimators`. 6. **Loss**: The loss function to use when updating the weights after each boosting iteration. - Available Options : `LINEAR`, `SQUARE`, `EXPONENTIAL` 7. **Seed**: Random seed. Use the same seed in order to reproduce the same results. 8. **Group By**: Columns to group by. ### Python #### USAGE ``` ada_boost_regression_train(table, feature_cols, label_col, max_depth=3, n_estimators=50, learning_rate=1.0, loss='linear', random_state=None , group_by=None) ``` #### INPUT 1. **table***: (Table) Training data in a Table. It must contain at least one column for labels. #### OUTPUT 1. **model**: (Model) Trained Adaboost Regression model. #### PARAMETER 1. **feature_cols***: Feature column names. Only values in numeric type are possible. * Type: *list[str]* 2. **label_col***: The column designated for the labels of data. It should be numeric type as it is for regression. * Type: *str* 3. **max_depth**: The maximum depth of the base estimator. In this Brightics Studio, the base estimator for Adaboost Regression model is Decision Tree Regression model. Note that it is one of the main parameters to tune to obtain good results by controlling the complexity of the base estimmators. * Type: *int* * Default / Range: 3 (value >= 2) 4. **n_estimators**: The maximum number of estimators at which boosting is terminated. In case of perfect fit, the learning procedure is stopped early. Increasing `n_estimators` increases the number of iterations, and allows the sample weights to gain greater amplitude. This translates into 1) more weak classifiers to combine at the end, and 2) more variations in the decision boundaries of these classifiers. Put together these effects lead to more complex decision boundaries. Note that it is one of the main parameters to tune to obtain good results. * Type: *int* * Default / Range: 50 (value >= 1) 5. **learning_rate**: Learning rate shrinks the contribution of each classifier by `learning_rate`. Decreasing the `learning_rate` reduces the amplitude of the sample weights at each step. This translates into smaller variations of the weighted data points and therefore fewer differences between the weak classifier decision boundaries. There is a trade-off between `learning_rate` and `n_estimators`. * Type: *float* * Default / Range: 1.0 (value >= 0.0) 6. **loss**: The loss function to use when updating the weights after each boosting iteration. * Type: *str* * Default / Range: linear ( linear | square | exponential ) 7. **random_state**: Random seed. Use the same seed in order to reproduce the same results. * Type: *int* 8. **group_by**: Columns to group by. * Type: *list[str]* ## Example ### VA **[Related Tutorial]** **[Sample Model]**
In this tutorial workflow, sample_iris data is used to train an adaboost regression. The generated model is afterward applied to a test data set to predict the value of _petal\_width_, by using Adaboost Regression Predict function. The parameter settings used in the function are shown below. ++Parameters++ 1. **Feature Columns***: sepal_length, sepal_width 2. **Label Column***: petal_width 3. **Maximum Depth**: 3 4. **Number of Estimators**: 50 5. **Learning Rate**: 1.0 6. **Loss**: LINEAR 7. **Seed**: None 8. **Group By**: None ### Python ``` from brightics.function.regression import ada_boost_regression_train input_table = inputs[0] result = ada_boost_regression_train(table=input_table, feature_cols=['sepal_length', 'sepal_width'], label_col='petal_width', max_depth=3, n_estimators=50, learning_rate=1.0, loss='linear', random_state=None, group_by=None) output = result['model'] ```
In this python script, sample_iris data is used to train an adaboost regression. The generated model can be applied to a test data set to predict the value of _petal\_width_, by using Adaboost Regression Predict function.
